ad_creative_link_descriptions:
We are inviting you to our annual conference Intercultural and Interfaith Dialogue, this year themed "Building Trust Among Future Communities".

Trust is a necessary element to advance bilateral and multilateral relationships including long-distance trade, partnerships for social and environmental development, to give mutual responses to crises and preserve global peace.

On November 11th, our outstanding guests will elaborate on the importance of trust in times of rising levels of populism, polarization and extremism on one side, and increasing levels of religiosity.

Among speakers who accepted our invitation, we are honored to present:

- Prof. Olivier Roy
- Chief Rabbi David Rosen
- Dr Maria del Mar Griera
- Dr Sarah Wolff
and many more.

The event will be held in Czernin Palace (The Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Republic) and online on our website. The registration is mandatory for in-person participation.

Find out the preliminary program and registration form here:  https://bit.ly/IC_Dialogue.

We thank our partner institution for cooperation: the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Republic, Anna Lindh Foundation Czech Network and Organisation of Islamic Cooperation (OIC).

Německé volby se uskuteční již v neděli, a tak je ten nejlepší čas si poslechnout nový díl našeho podcastu Kanzleramt!

Dnešním hostem Jakuba Eberleho byl Martin Jonáš, zpravodaj Česká televize v Německu, který v podcastu popisuje události a atmosféru kolem voleb přímo v centru dění. Dozvíte se například, jak se změnila německá politika od posledních voleb a jestli skutečně sledujeme posun k větší personalizaci a medializaci politiky, jako je tomu například ve Spojených státech. Řeč bude také o odkazu a osobě Angele Merkel. 

Podcast vzniká ve spolupráci s Voxpot a Friedrich-Ebert-Stiftung, zastoupení v České republice.

ad_creative_bodies:
We are happy to invite you to attend the online conference called Towards a Meaningful Change: Gendered Foreign Policy in Practice. The conference is held under the auspices of the Czech Minister of Foreign Affairs Tomáš Petříček and will be starting on November 4 at 9:30.
 
This conference focuses on “the day after”, namely on the everyday and institutional aspects of advancing gender norms in practice, while it is also reflecting on the contemporary challenges of the global backlash on women’s rights and the gendered impact of the COVID-19 pandemic. What mechanisms, setups, or procedures can contribute towards a meaningful and visible change in the practice of foreign policy? 

The conference will be launched with a series of high-level political and scholarly interventions. In the following panel discussions, distinguished speakers from around the world will offer diverse perspectives on the issues of the advancement of the women, peace and security agenda, women’s empowerment and gender equality in development cooperation, and the international dimension of tackling gender-based violence and supporting sexual and reproductive rights. Far from treating gender and women’s rights as a nuisance, we invite you to register to the conference and submit your written or video enquiry.
 
Find out more about the programme and speakers here: bit.ly/GenderCon

Register here: https://bit.ly/Gender_Registration

Srdečně vás zveme na online konferenci Towards a Meaningful Change: Gendered Foreign Policy in Practice. Konference se uskuteční pod záštitou ministra zahraničních věcí Tomáše Petříčka a bude zahájena 4. prosince od 9:30.

Konference se zaměřuje na „den poté”, konkrétně na každodenní a institucionální aspekty prosazování genderových norem v praxi. Také se snaží zamyslet nad aktuálními výzvami odmítání ženských práv ve světě a dopadu COVID-19 pandemie na chápání genderu. Jaké mechanismy nebo postupy mohou přispět ke smysluplné a viditelné změně v praktikách zahraničních politik? 

Konference bude zahájena řadou politických a vědeckých poznatků. V navazujících panelových diskusích nabídnou významní řečníci z celého světa rozmanité pohledy na otázky míru a bezpečnosti, posílení postavení žen v politice, genderové nerovnosti v rozvojové spolupráci, na mezinárodní rozměr boje proti násilí na základě genderu a podpory sexuálních a reprodukčních práv. 

Tímto vás zveme, abyste se na konferenci zaregistrovali a zároveň i máte možnost písemně nebo pomocí videa poslat svůj dotaz ohledně výše zmiňované problematiky. 

Registrovat se můžete zde: https://bit.ly/Gender_Registration

O celém programu a řečnících se můžete více dozvědět zde: bit.ly/GenderCon

ad_creative_bodies:
This Thursday, get ready for one of our chief events – Intercultural and Interfaith Dialogue.
 
We’ve already covered all the panels and speakers that will be taking part (more info here: bit.ly/Interkultur2020) and now we are introducing the choir that will play after the 1st panel:
 
The Civilizations Choir of Antakya is a multireligious ensemble formed after the backdrop of Turkey’s democratization process in the mid-2000s. The choir’s hometown Antakya located in Turkey near the Syrian border is ethnographically very diverse. That is one of the reasons why the choir was formed – to represent the Arab-speaking religious groups, and also to expose the uncertainties of ethnoreligiously defined citizenship.
 
If you want to listen to the band and want to learn more about its meaning, you can register here via this link: bit.ly/Interculture2020

ad_creative_bodies:
We are pleased to introduce you one of the panels of 
Intercultural and Interfaith Dialogue.

Intercultural and interfaith dialogues have become integral parts of political and diplomatic efforts. Panel "The Relevance of Religion in Diplomacy Today" aspires to highlight particular worldwide experience and lessons learned so far. What is the understanding, acceptance, and personal experience of religion among diplomats today? What kind of change or adjustment can we observe in this respect due to the current pandemic? 

The discussion will be led by Dr. Jan Šnaidauf from the  
Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Republic 

The speakers are:
- Dr. Robert Řehák, Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Republic
- Dr. Merete Bilde, European External Action Service - EEAS
- Prof. Peter Mandaville, George Mason University, USA
- Jasmina Bosto, KAICIID Dialogue Centre
- Hayder Al-Khoei, Al-Khoei Institute 

You may register via this link: http://bit.ly/Interculture2020

Je nám potěšením představit vám jeden z panelů v pořadí již páté konference Intercultural and Interfaith Dialogue.

Mezikulturní a mezináboženské dialogy jsou nedílnou součástí diplomatického úsilí. Panel s názvem „The Relevance of Religion in Diplomacy Today“ navazuje na dosud načerpané zkušenosti v této oblasti. Jak vnímají diplomati náboženství - na pracovní nebo i osobní úrovni? Co změnila současná pandemie?

Diskuzi povede Jan Šnaidauf z 
Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Republic.

Řečníky jsou:
- Dr. Robert Řehák, Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Czech Republic
- Dr. Merete Bilde, European External Action Service - EEAS
- Prof. Peter Mandaville, George Mason University, USA
- Jasmina Bosto, KAICIID Dialogue Centre
- Hayder Al-Khoei, Al-Khoei Institute

We are excited to introduce to you another of our speakers Dr. Kaoru Natsuda who will deliver speech on topic Japanese FDI and Management Transfer to Czechia on March 10th at European Union, Visegrad 4 and Japan.

Dr. Natsuda is a professor at the College of International Management, Ritsumeikan Asia Pacific University, Japan and a visiting professor at Budapest Business School (BGE), Hungary. His research interests include industrial development, rural development, and political economy in Asia and Central Europe. He serves as a Senior Associate editor of PSU Research Review and an editorial board member of International Journal of Development Issues.

We are pleased to introduce to you our first distinguished speaker Hiroyuki Akita, who will be delivering a speech on EU – Japan EPA, and EU – Japan Strategic Partnership Agreement at the European Union, Visegrad 4 and Japan on March 10th. 

Mr. Akita is a journalist and commentator of Nikkei Asian Review. He regularly writes commentaries, columns and analysis mainly on foreign international security affairs. He was Beijing Correspondent and Washington Chief Correspondent, where he reported many major political events. Moreover, he was an associate of US-Japan Program at Harvard University, where he conducted research on US-China-Japan relations.

In March 2019, he won the Vaughn-Ueda International Journalist Award, a prize for outstanding reporting of international affairs. He is an author of two books in Japanese: “Anryu (Power Game of US-China-Japan)” and “Ranryu (Strategic Competition of US-Japan and China)”.

Find out more about the programme of the upcoming conference here: bit.ly/Conference_Japan
